“east and west” became a stand-in for the exchange of goods. It
is perhaps no accident that the Silk Road extended from China
westward to the eastern Mediterranean. Another popular explanation
points to the restriction of commerce to the East and West Markets
in the Tang (618–907 CE) capital Chang’an (
